1771855629157413	1	itc:v3:AWKTMnkmSTJyZnQAAAAAQa2vVqtdbcAAAAEykwE		item.create	bn-2bh3	{"description":"Context\nThe current incremental PageRank entrypoint in crates/bones-triage/src/metrics/pagerank.rs intentionally falls back to full recompute because the prior implementation had correctness issues (especially around dangling-node mass) and also did full verification, eliminating performance gains.\n\nProblem\nWe need a true incremental algorithm that is both correct and measurably faster than full recompute on sparse/targeted graph edits, while preserving safety and deterministic output.\n\nGoals\n1) Restore a real incremental path in pagerank_incremental(...) for edge add/remove updates.\n2) Correctly account for global dangling-mass effects so score normalization remains stable (sum approx 1.0) and unaffected nodes are not silently wrong.\n3) Add robust fallback heuristics for cases where incremental work is likely slower or risky.\n4) Keep API compatibility for callers in bones-cli triage_support.\n\nImplementation Requirements\n- Rework incremental iteration to propagate rank deltas from a frontier and downstream closure, but include a global dangling contribution term each iteration.\n- Define explicit conditions that force full recompute (example candidates: very large affected set, low confidence initialization, high divergence estimate, extreme topology shifts).\n- Remove any mandatory full recompute verification in the steady-state incremental path; if validation is retained, make it optional/sampled and cheap.\n- Preserve method reporting semantics via PageRankMethod (Incremental vs IncrementalFallback vs Full) so telemetry/output remains meaningful.\n- Update module docs to describe the actual algorithm and safety model.\n\nTesting\n- Unit tests in crates/bones-triage/src/metrics/pagerank.rs covering:\n  - edge add/remove with and without dangling-status transitions\n  - unknown-item changes\n  - SCC behavior and score distribution invariants\n  - convergence and max-iter guardrails\n- Property/regression tests ensuring:\n  - score sum is approximately 1.0\n  - incremental output remains within tolerance of full recompute across randomized graph edits\n- Add targeted tests for dangling transitions (0->1 out-degree and 1->0 out-degree) because these are known failure modes.\n\nPerformance Validation\n- Add a reproducible benchmark or benchmark-like test harness comparing incremental vs full for representative change sizes.\n- Document break-even behavior (when incremental is beneficial vs when to fallback).\n- Acceptance target: incremental path should show clear speedup for small localized edits on medium/large graphs, without violating accuracy thresholds.\n\nAcceptance Criteria\n- pagerank_incremental performs real incremental computation for qualifying changes.\n- Correctness checks pass, including dangling-node transition scenarios.\n- Method field accurately reflects actual compute path used.\n- No regressions in existing triage-related tests.\n- A short design note is added (module docs or nearby comment block) explaining algorithm choices and fallback policy.","kind":"task","labels":["triage","pagerank","performance","correctness"],"size":"l","title":"Implement correct incremental PageRank with dangling-mass handling"}	blake3:bG8MlNo3Q6jGOMpp_eUPEkcbGlarn4In3qIeE_ga4W0
1771855720027454	1	itc:v3:AWKTMnkmSTJyZnQAAAAAQa2vVqtdbcAAAAEylAE		item.comment	bn-2bh3	{"body":"Recommended references to attach for correctness and algorithm design:\n\n1) Page, Brin, Motwani, Winograd (1999), The PageRank Citation Ranking: Bringing Order to the Web.\n   - Baseline definition, stochastic formulation, and normalization assumptions.\n\n2) Langville & Meyer (2006), Google's PageRank and Beyond.\n   - Practical numerical details (dangling handling, convergence behavior, implementation pitfalls).\n\n3) Gleich (2015), PageRank Beyond the Web (SIAM Review).\n   - Strong survey on variants, linear-system view, and convergence/correctness framing.\n\n4) Bahmani, Chowdhury, Goel (VLDB 2011), Fast Incremental and Personalized PageRank.\n   - Incremental/update-oriented approach and theoretical guidance for dynamic graph edits.\n\nReference implementations to use as test oracles (full recompute):\n- NetworkX pagerank\n- igraph page_rank\n\nNote: there is no single de facto standard incremental implementation used everywhere; safest validation strategy is comparing incremental results against full recompute within tolerance across randomized edit sequences, especially dangling-node transitions (0->1 and 1->0 out-degree).}"}	blake3:T2l7Jsb7ZfKojpW5ld72VVyW7K-T-Tl0hGL0ZeXXTyY
1771856178069579	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEzFA		item.create	bn-m91g	{"description":"Review all help outputs for subcommands and update.\nKeep in mind the help is for agents that have never seen this tool before.\nUse consistent language. Use tool branding; not \"items\", \"bones\".\nTODO tasks are \"bones\" in a \"pile.\"\nAvoid unnecessary details.\nShow example usage.\n\nExample for create --help:\n\n> Create a new work item and append an item.create event.\n\nSuggested change:\n\n> Add a new bone to the pile.\n> \n> Example usage:\n> \n>   bn create \\\n>     --title \"Title of your bone here\" \\\n>     --description \"Some long, detailed subscription.\" \\>     --label first-label --label second-label \\>     --size xl","kind":"task","labels":["help"],"title":"audit and update help output"}	blake3:iVJ1Mfawq_JpyVKrbmpFpWdxjmgRNpmbseBoqK2qI58
